# {{LOOP_NAME}}

Scaffolded via `bl new go-test-basic`. A go-test-gated bounded loop: an agent
edits `seed/example.go` until `go test ./...` passes, or the loop halts at
`bounds.yaml`'s `max_iterations`.

## Files

- `loop.yaml` — the manifest (name, gate, runner, bounds).
- `bounds.yaml` — safety bounds (max iterations, no-progress window, etc).
- `PROMPT.md` — the task spec given to the agent. Edit this first.
- `STATE.md` — cross-lap memory, populated automatically.
- `seed/` — the workspace the agent edits (`example.go`, `go.mod`) plus the
  gate anchor test (`example_test.go`, don't edit).
- `cassettes/default.json` — a keyless, deterministic stub-agent recording
  used by `bl run` (via `runner.default: stub` in `loop.yaml`).
- `run.sh` / `wreck.sh` — standalone bash versions of the loop that need no
  engine at all: `run.sh` is gated, `wreck.sh` deliberately removes the gate
  to show why gating matters.

## Quickstart

```bash
cd {{LOOP_NAME}}
bl run .                 # via the bounded-loops engine (keyless stub runner)
./run.sh                 # or standalone, no engine required
```

Replace `PROMPT.md`, `seed/`, and `cassettes/default.json` with your own
task once you're ready to move past the starter example.

## Note on `gate.run`

`loop.yaml`'s `gate.run` is `cd seed && go test ./...`, not a bare
`go test ./...` — the bounded-loops engine always runs the gate command
with its working directory set to the loop's scratch workspace ROOT (the
directory whose child is `seed/`), not `seed/` itself. `go test ./...`
needs a `go.mod` at its own working directory, so the `cd seed &&` prefix
is required (unlike `pytest -q`, which recurses into subdirectories on its
own).
